Q: How to load Flutter assets in Android A: <p>Looks like the <code>AssetManager</code> is directly available simply by using <code>assets</code>! For example:</p>
<pre><code>class MainActivity : FlutterActivity() {
    override fun configureFlutterEngine(flutterEngine: FlutterEngine) {
        super.configureFlutterEngine(flutterEngine)

        val assetManager: AssetManager = assets

        ...
    }
}
</code></pre>

Q: Implementation of the (modular) visitor design pattern A: <blockquote>
<p>I rode about some &quot;modular&quot; visitor design pattern variation, but I don't know if I am on the right track</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I believe you are thinking of the Acyclic Visitor Pattern, which relies on <em>downcasting</em> the visitor to break the cyclic dependency between the Visitor interface and the expressions to visit.</p>
<p>It generally looks like:</p>
<pre class="lang-cpp prettyprint-override"><code>class Foo: public AstPiece {
public:
    void accept(AstPieceVisitor&amp; visitor) override {
        if (auto v = dynamic_cast&lt;FooVisitor*&gt;(&amp;visitor)) {
            v-&gt;visit_foo(*this);
        }
        //  Your choice of silently moving on, or considering this an error.
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Downcasting is not very idiomatic in Rust, and the Acyclic Visitor Pattern is quite a mouthful.</p>
<hr />
<p>If the goal is simply to ignore parts of the AST, the idiomatic Rust API would be to provide a default do-nothing implementation for the methods of the visitor trait.</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>trait AstVisitor {
    fn visit_select(&amp;mut self, _) {
        //  Do nothing.
    }

    ...
}
</code></pre>
<p>You can even help users catch (at run-time, but better than nothing) unintentionally ignored pieces by calling <code>self.visit_unimplemented(&quot;visit_select&quot;)</code> so that users worried about missing pieces can detect they've missed something.</p>
